item.title: Rytidosperma duttonianum
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: Open grassland species not uncommon on heavy basalt-derived soils. Flower heads are robust and 'chunky' looking, with spikelets enclosed within large straw-coloured glumes. Mature florets provide useful identification (see photos), with body of lemma turning golden brown (thus, Brown-backed Wallaby Grass). Lemma row of hair above callus (middle row) is variably complete, often hairs sparse across centre of the lemma surface. Awn strongly twisted and shining bronze colour.

item.title: Tribulus terrestris
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: Nasty weed across inland areas of Australia, infamous for its ferocious spiny fruits that have the ability to puncture tyres and pierce through thin footwear. In Victoria, seems to prefer sandy soils. Only this single plant found at this site (promptly removed and disposed of). Likely arrived on vehicle tyres.

item.title: Rytidosperma racemosum var. racemosum
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: This species is commonly encountered and easy to identify. The inflorescence appear raceme-like (hence the name), as floral spikelets are spaced along the flowering stem. The floret has an obvious naked patch on the lemma body, with hairs only on the margins. The lemma lobes are long, tapering abruptly to produce filiform points.

item.title: Rytidosperma geniculatum
item.dc:creator: chrisl
item.description: Some key features worth remembering for this species, include the often widely spreading lobes of the lemma (especially when mature), the rather even length of hairs over the lemma body that are not in obvious transverse lines, the sub-equal length of the lemma awn to the lemma lobes (often much longer in other species), and the geniculate (bent) flowering stem at a node near the base (see 3rd photo). The leaves are fine, hairy and tightly in-rolled.
